Got it — bare `html, css, js` folder is totally fine to start from. 

You don’t need React, Vite, etc to publish to NPM. You just need 3 things: `src/`, `dist/`, and `package.json`.

Here’s the minimal setup to go from "folder" → "installable npm package":

*1. New folder structure*
your-svg-lib/
  src/
    index.js        <- your library code
  dist/             <- will be generated by build
  index.html        <- your manual test page, not published
  package.json
  README.md
  LICENSE
  .gitignore
*2. Minimal `package.json`*
{
  "name": "svg-canvas",         // change this to something unique
  "version": "0.1.0",
  "description": "Canvas-like API for SVG",
  "main": "dist/index.umd.js",
  "module": "dist/index.esm.js",
  "exports": {
    ".": {
      "import": "./dist/index.esm.js",
      "require": "./dist/index.umd.js"
    }
  },
  "files": ["dist"],            // only publish dist/
  "keywords": ["svg", "graphics", "vector", "vanilla"],
  "license": "MIT",
  "scripts": {
    "build": "esbuild src/index.js --bundle --minify --format=esm --outfile=dist/index.esm.js && esbuild src/index.js --bundle --minify --format=iife --global-name=SVG --outfile=dist/index.umd.js",
    "prepublishOnly": "npm run build"
  },
  "devDependencies": {
    "esbuild": "^0.23.0"
  }
}
`global-name=SVG` means `<script>` users get `window.SVG.fillRect()`

*3. Move your code to `src/index.js`*
Export your class/function so it can be imported.
// src/index.js
const NAMESPACE = "http://www.w3.org/2000/svg";

export class SVG {
  constructor(element) {
    this.element = element;
  }

  #mapAttr(el, keys, args) { /* your existing code */ }

  fillRect(x, y, width, height, fill, stroke) {
    const rect = document.createElementNS(NAMESPACE, "rect");
    this.#mapAttr(rect, ["x","y","width","height","fill","stroke"], arguments);
    this.element.appendChild(rect);
    return rect;
  }

  fillEllipse(cx, cy, rx, ry, fill, stroke) { /* ... */ }
  fillPolygon(points, fill, stroke, strokeWidth) { /* ... */ }
  fillPath(d, fill, stroke, strokeWidth) { /* ... */ }
  fillText(text, x, y, fill, fontSize) { /* ... */ }
}
`export class SVG` is what makes it work for `import`.

*4. Build it once*
npm install
npm run build
That gives you `dist/index.esm.js` + `dist/index.umd.js`. Only `dist/` gets published.

*5. Test it locally before publishing*
`index.html` - not published, just for you:
<script type="module">
  import { SVG } from './src/index.js'; // use src during dev

  const svg = new SVG(document.querySelector('svg'));
  svg.fillRect(10,10,100,50,'red','black');
</script>
*6. Publish*
npm login
npm publish --access public
Done. People can now do `npm i svg-canvas`

*.gitignore + .npmignore*
`.gitignore`
node_modules
dist
`.npmignore`
src
index.html
node_modules
Rule: Git keeps everything. NPM only gets `dist + package.json + README + LICENSE`.

---

You’re basically 10 mins away from v0.1.0 on npm. 

